<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-03-01T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-03-01T17:00:00-05:00" n="50" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d50">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 600.119/561</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-03-01T22:00:00+00:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">March 1, 1918, 10 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received March 1, 7
                                    p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>8865. War Trade Board [from <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1">Sheldon</persName>]:</p>
                            <p>No. 216. Your 113.<note n="1" xml:id="d50fn1">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_963">p.
                                    963</ref>.</note> Article 2. You mention representatives in
                                northern neutrals of United States and Great Britain only. Is it not
                                your intention that these local joint committees shall comprise also
                                French and Italian representatives and that the joint plan as per
                                your 113 shall later apply to all the Allies rather than just Great
                                Britain and the United States? I should strongly approve extending
                                it to the four cobelligerents. Section 6. Do you intend me to become
                                officially a member of the existing Contraband Committee? Your
                                reference to this in section 7 leads me to think that you do. I
                                should recommend that an inter-Allied blockade committee be set up
                                as soon as possible, but would suggest that it be called, say,
                                inter-Allied export control committee as a more palatable name to
                                the northern neutrals. The Foreign Office agree to the general plan
                                outlined in your No. 113.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>